jp.co.rakuten.util.multiindex
Class OrderedUniqueIndex<K extends java.lang.Comparable<K>,T>

java.lang.Object
  jp.co.rakuten.util.collection.avltree.UnmodifiableAvlTreeMap<K,Record<T>>
      jp.co.rakuten.util.multiindex.UniqueIndex<K,T>
          jp.co.rakuten.util.multiindex.OrderedUniqueIndex<K,T>
Type Parameters:
T - Target data-type.
All Implemented Interfaces:
StdContainer<Pair<K,Record<T>>>, StdMap<K,Record<T>>, StdRandom<Pair<K,Record<T>>,K>, StdRandomStartWith<Pair<K,Record<T>>,K>, StdRandomUnique<Pair<K,Record<T>>,K>, StdSequence<Pair<K,Record<T>>>, Index<T>
public class OrderedUniqueIndex<K extends java.lang.Comparable<K>,T>
extends UniqueIndex<K,T>
implements StdMap<K,Record<T>>

The index is sorted in order of specified field.

Specifying field must be unique. 
 
The case of random access by the key using raw iterator(flexible).
 OrderedUniqueIndex<Integer,MyData> unique = (OrderedUniqueIndex<Integer,MyData>)multiIndex.index(0);
 StdIterator<Pair<Integer,Record<MyData>>> it = unique.find(new Integer(3));
 Record<MyData> r = it.get().second;
 MyData d = r.get();
      :  
 
 
The case of sequential access using CompatibleIterable (simple)
 OrderedUniqueIndex<Integer,MyData> unique = (OrderedUniqueIndex<Integer,MyData>)multiIndex.index(0);
 for ( Pair<Integer,Record<MyData>> p : new CompatibleIterable<Pair<Integer,Record<MyData>>>(unique) ) { 
   Record<MyData> r = p.second;
   MyData d = r.get();
        :  
 }
 
 
The case of range access using CompatibleIterable (from 3 to 5)
 OrderedUniqueIndex<Integer,MyData> unique = (OrderedUniqueIndex<Integer,MyData>)multiIndex.index(0);
 StdIterator<Pair<Integer,Record<MyData>>> rangeFirst = unique.find(3);
 StdIterator<Pair<Integer,Record<MyData>>> rangeLast  = unique.upperBound(5);
 for ( Pair<Integer,Record<MyData>> p : new CompatibleIterable<Pair<Integer,Record<MyData>>>(rangeFirst,rangeLast) ) { 
   Record<MyData> r = p.second;
   MyData d = r.get();
        :  
 }

hiroaki.kubota@mail.rakuten.co.jp
